episodes.title: Welcome to the New Modern Love
episodes.subtitle: Love is going to sound a little different this season. Tune into the first episode on Oct. 14, with new episodes every Wednesday.

episodes.title: Confronting Race, Religion and Her Heart | With Zawe Ashton
episodes.subtitle: In this week’s essay, Lilian Oben writes about how essential it is to be seen in relationships — to be able to take up space, without being asked to change who we are. Her essay is read by Zawe Ashton ("Betrayal").

episodes.title: Why Can’t Men Say ‘I Love You’ to Each Other? | With Ncuti Gatwa
episodes.subtitle:
Do you tell your friends you love them? And do you say it like that, using those words? Is it easy for you to say? Is it fraught?
Ricardo Jaramillo takes those questions on in this week’s essay. It’s read by Ncuti Gatwa, who stars in “Sex Education” on Netflix.

episodes.title: Race Wasn't An Issue To Him, Which Was An Issue To Me With Lorraine Toussaint | Encore
episodes.subtitle: Lorraine Toussaint ("The Glorias") reads an essay by Kim McLarin. Then, we catch up with Kim to hear how she is doing in this moment.

episodes.title: Researching Jenna, Discovering Myself | With Hasan Minhaj
episodes.subtitle: Hasan Minhaj ("Patriot Act with Hasan Minhaj") reads Brian Goedde's essay about a man investigating his own breakup.

episodes.title: The Language Of Love With Saoirse Ronan | Encore
episodes.subtitle: Saoirse Ronan ("Little Women") reads an essay about how a language barrier impacts the relationship between a young woman and an Iraqi doctor. This is an encore presentation.

episodes.title: How ‘Lolita’ Freed Me From My Own Humbert | With Jameela Jamil
episodes.subtitle:
"Lolita," Vladimir Nabokov’s novel about a man’s sexual obsession with a young girl, is famously controversial. But when Bindu Bansinath started to read it, it unexpectedly became a kind of road map for her, showing her a way out of the situation she was in. 
Jameela Jamil ("I Weigh") reads her piece.

episodes.title: Alone In A Pandemic
episodes.subtitle:
Living alone can be liberating, maddening, joyful ... lonely.  It also might feel very different today than it did several months ago.
This episode features stories from people who live alone, telling us how they are doing right now.

episodes.title: To Fall In Love With Anyone, Do This | Encore
episodes.subtitle:
If you're running out of things to do at home — or if you just need a break from stress and worry — we have a suggestion. Listen to this week's episode featuring Gillian Jacobs and Mandy Len Catron, and then try the 36 questions that (may) lead to love. 
You can find the 36 questions here: https://nyti.ms/2SFbICi

episodes.title: Years Ago, My Sister Vanished. I See Her Whenever I Want. | With Daisy Edgar-Jones
episodes.subtitle: Daisy Edgar-Jones (Hulu's "Normal People") reads Kyleigh Leddy's essay, about the online presence people leave behind.

episodes.title: Sometimes It's Not You, Or The Math | With Laura Prepon
episodes.subtitle: What if all the conventional wisdom about why you are single is wrong? Laura Prepon ("You And I, As Mothers") reads Sara Eckel's essay.

episodes.title: Your Stories of Love During The Pandemic: Part II
episodes.subtitle: We hear more of your stories about how the COVID-19 outbreak has changed your relationships with one another.

episodes.title: Modern Love Presents: Sugar Calling
episodes.subtitle: Modern Love presents an excerpt of the first episode of “Sugar Calling." Hear Cheryl Strayed in conversation with the author George Saunders, her old friend and mentor from graduate school.

episodes.title: Somewhere Inside, a Path to Empathy | With Daniel Radcliffe
episodes.subtitle:
When you’re in a new relationship, you’re always trying to present your best self. But anyone who’s been in a relationship for awhile knows that you can’t keep the act up forever. 
David Finch writes about that in his essay, which is read by Daniel Radcliffe. Daniel stars in the upcoming "Unbreakable Kimmy Schmidt" interactive special on Netflix.

episodes.title: Your Stories of Love During The Pandemic
episodes.subtitle: Listeners share stories of how their relationships have changed during the coronavirus outbreak.

episodes.title: How Bibliophiles Flirt | With Uzo Aduba
episodes.subtitle:
There's something wonderful about sharing your favorite books with the person you're falling in love with. And Karla Derus was a longtime book lover, dating a man who was also a big reader. But Karla also had a secret. 
Emmy-winning actress Uzo Aduba ("Mrs. America") reads Karla's essay.

episodes.title: When Your Greatest Romance Is A Friendship | Encore
episodes.subtitle: Ali Fazal ("Victoria and Abul") tells the story of an unlikely friendship between a man and his elderly neighbor. This is an encore presentation.

episodes.title: Modern Love Presents: Shipwrecked
episodes.subtitle:
Could you use a little extra comfort and love from afar right now? We thought so. We're sharing an episode of another WBUR podcast, "Endless Thread." This is a story about processing grief, and where we turn when the people closest to us don't seem to know what to do or say to help us move forward.
If you enjoy this episode, subscribe to "Endless Thread" wherever you get your podcasts. More info here: https://smarturl.it/endlessthread

episodes.title: Recognizing What They Had, 20 Years Too Late | With Gugu Mbatha-Raw
episodes.subtitle: Gugu Mbatha-Raw ("The Morning Show," "Misbehaviour") reads an essay about a friendship between two people who meet in a pub in Notting Hill.

episodes.title: The Kindness, And Xanax, Of Strangers | With Lesley Manville
episodes.subtitle: Lesley Manville ("Ordinary Love") reads an essay by Sally Hoskins about finding an unexpected support group in a hospital waiting room.

episodes.title: I Saw A Playhouse, My Daughter Saw A Jail | With Brian Cox
episodes.subtitle: Brian Cox (HBO's "Succession") reads an essay about a father grappling with how to protect his child, but also let her live her life.

episodes.title: Just For Tonight, Pretend You Don't Know Me | With Nick Kroll
episodes.subtitle: What if you had to pretend your partner was a stranger for a day? Would you fall in love again? Nick Kroll ("Olympic Dreams") reads Tim Kreider's essay.

episodes.title: Tiny Love Stories For Valentine's Day
episodes.subtitle: This Valentine's Day, we're bringing you an episode made up of Tiny Love Stories — stories told in no more than 100 words.

episodes.title: When Cupid Is A Prying Journalist | With Susan Kelechi Watson
episodes.subtitle: Susan Kelechi Watson (NBC's "This Is Us," "A Beautiful Day In The Neighborhood") reads Deborah Copaken's essay about how a lost love leads to an unexpected connection years later.

episodes.title: Dedicated To Two Women | With Terry Crews
episodes.subtitle: Terry Crews ("Brooklyn Nine-Nine") reads an essay by Brendan Halpin, about trying to find love again after loss.

episodes.title: A Role I Was Born To Play | With Tan France
episodes.subtitle: Tan France ("Queer Eye," "Next in Fashion") reads an essay by Evan James, about a man finding his role within his family.

episodes.title: My Secret Left Me Unable To Help | With Jessalyn Gilsig
episodes.subtitle: Love is about trust. But have you ever been tempted to breach that trust? To read someone's diary, check their text messages, or read their emails? Jessalyn Gilsig reads an essay by Joyce Maynard about facing that temptation.

episodes.title: Take Me As I Am, Whoever I Am With Rebecca Hall | Encore
episodes.subtitle: Rebecca Hall who stars in the upcoming movie "The Night House," reads a story about dating -- while manic. This is an encore presentation.

episodes.title: Need To Find Me? Ask My Ham Man. | With Jenny Slate
episodes.subtitle: Jenny Slate ("Stage Fright," "Little Weirds") reads an essay by Catherine Down about the family you find when living far from home.

episodes.title: An Interlude Of Clarity With Judd Apatow | Encore
episodes.subtitle: Director Judd Apatow reads an essay about a date that goes very wrong. This is an encore presentation.

episodes.title: The Race Grows Sweeter With Mary Chapin Carpenter | Encore
episodes.subtitle: Singer-songwriter Mary Chapin Carpenter reads a story by Eve Pell, about finding new love later in life. This is an encore presentation.

episodes.title: Nursing A Wound With Jake Gyllenhaal | Encore
episodes.subtitle: Jake Gyllenhaal ("Stronger") tells the story of a man recovering from heartbreak in a pediatrics wing.

episodes.title: Are You My Husband? | With Renée Elise Goldsberry
episodes.subtitle: Renée Elise Goldsberry ("Waves") reads an essay about a woman and her husband navigating the aftermath of his traumatic brain injury.

episodes.title: Never Tell Our Business To Strangers | With Ruth Wilson
episodes.subtitle:
"Never tell our business to strangers." That's what Jennifer Mascia was told growing up. But it wasn't until she was an adult that she learned the reason why.
Ruth Wilson (HBO's "His Dark Materials") reads Jennifer's essay about discovering a dark family secret.

episodes.title: Who's Allowed To Hold Hands? | With Alicia Keys
episodes.subtitle: "I’ve noticed that there is a strange hierarchy of handholding that dictates who gets to express physical affection without repercussions," Nicole Dennis-Benn writes in this week's Modern Love story. It's read by 15-time Grammy Award winning artist Alicia Keys, whose new single is called "Show Me Love."

episodes.title: Sharing A Cab, And My Toes With Greta Gerwig | Encore
episodes.subtitle: Greta Gerwig ("Little Women") reads Julia Anne Miller's essay, about sharing an unusual cab ride in New York City. This is an encore presentation.

episodes.title: Modern Love Presents: Kind World
episodes.subtitle: We want to introduce you to another podcast we think you might love, called Kind World. It features stories of life-changing acts of kindness. And this week's story features a story from the US/ Mexico border.

episodes.title: Waiting For The Wall To Crumble | With Kelly McCreary
episodes.subtitle: Kelly McCreary ("Grey's Anatomy") reads an essay about a chance meeting on a bus that leads to a decades-long relationship.

episodes.title: The Triangle's Sharpest Point | With Zawe Ashton
episodes.subtitle:
We make decisions every day that shape our lives in small ways. But it's rare to face a real crossroads — a choice between living one life, and living another that's entirely different. 
Zawe Ashton ("Betrayal") reads an essay by Ingrid Maitland, who writes about making a choice like that.

episodes.title: We'll Meet Again In Five Years | With Regina King
episodes.subtitle: Regina King (HBO's "Watchmen") reads an essay by a woman who thinks she's met the right person for her — several years too early.

episodes.title: Words With (I Wish We Were More Than) Friends | With Ben Platt
episodes.subtitle:
When he was working in Nevada, Justin Race met a woman he thought was perfect for him. The only problem? They had only ever talked to each other through Words With Friends.
Justin's essay is read by Tony-winning actor Ben Platt, who stars in the new show "The Politician" on Netflix.

episodes.title: He's Going Back To His Former Wife. Sort Of. | With Marisa Tomei
episodes.subtitle: Marisa Tomei ("The Rose Tattoo") reads an essay by Judith Newman about a woman fulfilling her husband's unusual dying wish.

episodes.title: Rallying To Keep The Game Alive | Live At CitySpace
episodes.subtitle:
In 2013, Ann Leary wrote an essay about a rough patch in her marriage. We turned it into an episode of the Modern Love Podcast. And now, Ann's story been adapted for television. 
In this episode, we revisit actress Connie Nielsen's performance of Ann's essay. Then, we'll hear a live conversation between Ann, Modern Love editor Daniel Jones, and podcast producer Caitlin O'Keefe. They talk about what happened next for Ann and her husband, and what it was like for Ann to have her essay adapted for the Modern Love television show.

episodes.title: How 30 Blocks Became 30 Years | With Peter Sarsgaard
episodes.subtitle: Peter Sarsgaard ("The Sound of Silence") reads an essay about the relationship between a man with spinal muscular atrophy and his wife of more than 30 years.

episodes.title: First I Met My Children, Then My Girlfriend. They’re Related. | With Kal Penn
episodes.subtitle:
When Aaron Long donated sperm twenty-five years ago, he didn't realize that one day he would discover that he had ten biological children. But that's what happened when he signed up for 23andMe.
Kal Penn stars in the NBC comedy "Sunnyside". He reads Aaron's essay.

episodes.title: Screens Between Us With Issa Rae | Encore
episodes.subtitle: Issa Rae reads an essay about the intimacy and distance synonymous with online dating.

episodes.title: The Tallest Man I Ever Loved | With Andrew Rannells
episodes.subtitle: Andrew Rannells has been nominated for two Tony Awards. He starred in HBO's "Girls." But before any of that, he was just like a lot of 20-somethings — trying to make his career happen, and dreaming about his perfect boyfriend.

episodes.title: Seeing The World Through My Wife's Eyes With David Oyelowo | Encore
episodes.subtitle: "Don't Let Go" star David Oyelowo reads an essay about a blind man navigating his marriage. This is an encore presentation.

episodes.title: My Platonic Romance On The Psych Ward | With Miriam Shor
episodes.subtitle:
This week's essay is about a deep, enduring friendship that starts in an unlikely place. Jeannie Vanasco writes about her relationship with a woman named Anita in her essay, "My Platonic Romance on the Psych Ward."
It's read by actress and director Miriam Shor, who stars in TV Land’s “Younger" and the upcoming Netflix film "Lost Girls."

episodes.title: Despite The Losses, So Much Gained | With Marsha Stephanie Blake
episodes.subtitle: When people first come into our lives, it's impossible to know how important they'll become. Leah Keith writes about a man who came to matter a great deal to her in her essay, which is read by Marsha Stephanie Blake ("When They See Us")

episodes.title: In A Charmed Life, A Road Less Traveled | With Nikolaj Coster-Waldau
episodes.subtitle: Nikolaj Coster-Waldau ("Game of Thrones") reads an essay about a man's long relationship with his wife — before and after a car accident that changed their lives.

episodes.title: The Night Girl Finds A Day Boy | With Logan Browning
episodes.subtitle:
A lot of things can get in the way of love -- distance, money issues, being in different places in your life. But this week's essayist, Amanda Gefter, writes about facing a very different kind of challenge.
It's read by Logan Browning (Netflix's "Dear White People").

episodes.title: Could We Try Again? | With Marcia Cross
episodes.subtitle:
If Meredith Hall had to point to the year that her life changed, she would probably say that it was 1965. She was sixteen that year, and pregnant with a son.
But more than two decades later, in 1987, her life changed again -- and that's the year she writes about in her essay. It's read by Marcia Cross ("Desperate Housewives," "Quantico").

episodes.title: He's Playing Our Song | With Amanda Seyfried
episodes.subtitle:
High school love is awkward, nervous -- and often unforgettable. It doesn't usually last. But in this week's essay, Mariclare Lawson writes about a high school love that broke all the rules.
It's read by Amanda Seyfried ("The Art of Racing in the Rain.")

episodes.title: At What Age Is Love Enthralling? | With Jessica Walter
episodes.subtitle: Jessica Walter ("Archer," "Arrested Development") reads an essay by Sophy Burnham about how an unexpected encounter makes her consider how love and desire change with age.

episodes.title: A Tattoo For The Living | With Zosia Mamet
episodes.subtitle: Alana Dakin writes about two different tattoos in her essay "A Tattoo for the Living", which is read by Zosia Mamet ("Tales of the City.")

episodes.title: An Empty Heart | With Zoe Lister-Jones | Encore
episodes.subtitle: Zoe Lister-Jones (CBS's "Life in Pieces," "Band-Aid") reads renowned novelist Lily King's story about the silver lining of heartbreak.

episodes.title: An Affection Multiplier | With Zachary Quinto
episodes.subtitle: Can a tiny dog change the dynamics of a marriage? Zachary Quinto ("NOS4A2") reads Bob Morris's essay.

episodes.title: Platonic, Until Death Do Us Part | With John Cameron Mitchell
episodes.subtitle: What do you do when you're struggling to find a romantic relationship as deep as the relationship you have with your best friend? John Cameron Mitchell ("Anthem: Homunculus") reads Ephi Stempler's essay about a man considering a platonic life partnership.

episodes.title: Encore | The Doorman With Cecily Strong
episodes.subtitle: Saturday Night Live's Cecily Strong reads a story about a woman's friendship with her doorman. This is an encore presentation.

episodes.title: Misery Loves Fried Chicken | With William Jackson Harper
episodes.subtitle:
How have you gotten through your worst breakups? Tinder? New hobbies? Cheap alcohol? Wallowing in Taylor Swift albums?
William Jackson Harper ("The Good Place," "Midsommar") is back to read Mark McDevitt's piece about two breakup buddies.

episodes.title: What Luck Means Now | With Jacki Weaver
episodes.subtitle: What does luck mean to you? And how does that change depending on your circumstances? That's what Joyce Maynard writes about in this week's essay. It's read by two-time Academy Award nominee Jacki Weaver ("Perpetual Grace, LTD").

episodes.title: We Survived The Storm | With Ginnifer Goodwin
episodes.subtitle: When you're dealing with a tragedy, it can feel like you would do anything for an ordinary day. But those ordinary days can come with their own complications. Ginnifer Goodwin ("The Twilight Zone") reads Monica Wesolowska's essay.

episodes.title: The Wisdom Of The Moving Man | With Lake Bell
episodes.subtitle:
When we take stock of the people who matter most to us, there are the spouses, the family members, the best friends, the partners. And then there are the people who aren’t any of those things, but who change our lives anyway.
Emily Raboteau's essay is about one of those people. It's read by Lake Bell ("Bless this Mess.")

episodes.title: Agreeing To Accept And Move On | With Sarah Goldberg
episodes.subtitle: Under normal circumstances, trying to find love can be challenging -- and stressful. And for Elizabeth Koster, the pressure was even more intense. Sarah Goldberg (HBO's "Barry") reads Elizabeth's essay.

episodes.title: Love Means Never Having To Say ... Anything | With Pedro Pascal
episodes.subtitle: Love thrives on good communication. It can take many forms -- but what happens when you suddenly lose what was once your primary means of communication? Pedro Pascal ("King Lear," "Game of Thrones") reads Jamison's essay.

episodes.title: Talking to My Fiancé About My New Girlfriend | With DeWanda Wise
episodes.subtitle:
What happens when you know you want to marry someone, but you are also are falling in love with someone else? Is there a way for you to have everything?
Sophie Lucido Johnson's essay is read by DeWanda Wise ("She's Gotta Have It").

episodes.title: Race Wasn't An Issue To Him, Which Was An Issue To Me | With Lorraine Toussaint
episodes.subtitle:
Interracial relationships come with their own complexities, and there are a lot of questions that come up. Questions like: How does your partner think about race? How do you talk about it? What works, and what doesn't?
Kim McLarin writes about race and dating in her piece, which is read by Lorraine Toussaint ("The Village").

episodes.title: Encore | Sharing The Shame With Anna Chlumsky
episodes.subtitle: Anna Chlumsky ("Veep") reads Brooks Rinehart's essay, on 90 days that changed the entire course of one family's life.

episodes.title: Ah, To Be Old, Male, And Single | With Natasha Lyonne
episodes.subtitle: When it comes to dating, Amy Cohen says this: "We all need to be reincarnated as an older Jewish man with an apartment on the Upper East Side.” Natasha Lyonne ("Russian Doll") reads Amy's essay about the difference between her 76-year-old father's dating life and her own.

episodes.title: Comfort, If Not A Cure | With Nazanin Boniadi
episodes.subtitle: How much can you give of yourself before it’s too much? And what do you do when you reach your limit? Nazanin Boniadi ("Hotel Mumbai") reads Tara Ebrahimi's essay.

episodes.title: Another Voice Had Come Between Us | With Catherine O'Hara
episodes.subtitle: Catherine O'Hara ("Schitt's Creek") reads Patricia Morrisroe's essay, about a piece of technology that complicates a marriage.

episodes.title: Refreshing A Mother's Memory With Love | With Zoe Saldana
episodes.subtitle:
Dementia can alter someone's personality and change how how they interact with the world. But sometimes, it can also lead to moments of profound connection. 
Jenny McPhee writes about one of those moments in her piece, which is read by Zoe Saldana.

episodes.title: Playing Role Reversal With My Therapist | With Isabelle Huppert
episodes.subtitle: Therapists' offices are supposed to be places where you can be both vulnerable and safe. But what happens when your therapist crosses a line? That happened to Julianna Baggott -- and she writes about it an an essay that's read by Isabelle Huppert ("Greta").

episodes.title: Security In A Bright Yellow Suitcase | With Christina Hendricks
episodes.subtitle:
You know the phase. The one when you're going back and forth between your place and your partner's, and you have to bring all your stuff with you. 
But when is it time to make a change? Deanna Clevesy's essay is read by Christina Hendricks ("Good Girls").

episodes.title: Your Dog Has Seen Me Naked | With William Jackson Harper
episodes.subtitle:
Have you ever dated someone living in a studio apartment with a pet? If so, how did you handle the logistics around sex?
Ryan Pfeffer writes about how he dealt with that situation in his essay, which was performed by William Jackson Harper ("The Good Place") in front of a live audience at the Huntington Avenue Theatre in Boston.

episodes.title: Part II: My Wife Said You May Want to Marry Me | With André Holland
episodes.subtitle:
Last week, you heard an essay by Amy Krouse Rosenthal -- "You May Want to Marry my Husband." It was published just days before she died of ovarian cancer.
Today, André Holland of "High Flying Bird" reads the essay her husband Jason wrote in response last summer, and we hear from Jason himself about how he's doing today.

episodes.title: Part I: You May Want to Marry My Husband
episodes.subtitle: Debra Winger reads the late Amy Krouse Rosenthal's essay about her fairytale love story, which was cut short by cancer. This is an encore presentation.

episodes.title: Oscars Playlist
episodes.subtitle: We're celebrating the 91st Academy Awards by revisiting two of our favorite episodes featuring nominated actors. We'll hear pieces read by Rachel Weisz of "The Favourite," and Willem Dafoe, of "At Eternity's Gate."

episodes.title: Rallying To Keep The Game Alive | With Connie Nielsen
episodes.subtitle: It's easy to single out the biggest decisions in a life. But this week's essay by Ann Leary is about little choices, that you might not think about very much in the moment, that end up slowly changing everything.  It's read by Connie Nielsen ("I Am the Night").

episodes.title: A Kiss Deferred | With Joanna Kulig
episodes.subtitle: Nikolina Kulidzan was twelve years old when she fell in love for the first time. Not long after, the Bosnian War changed her life forever. Her essay is read by Joanna Kulig ("Cold War").

episodes.title: What The Sea Took Away | With Carmen Ejogo
episodes.subtitle: How do you talk to your children about loss? What secrets do you keep, and for how long? And when do you decide to tell them everything? Emily Listfield faces those questions in her essay, read by Carmen Ejogo ("True Detective.")

episodes.title: Maternal Wisdom (5 Pounds' Worth) | With Gillian Anderson
episodes.subtitle: When you think back to sex ed class, it's not hard to come up with a couple of memories that might have scarred you for life. But actor Gillian Anderson reads an essay that shows it can be equally scarring for the parents.

episodes.title: Modern Love Holiday Playlist
episodes.subtitle: Happy Holidays from all of us at Modern Love! We will be back with brand new episodes in 2019, but today, we're bringing you a playlist of our favorite holiday episodes from the past two years.

episodes.title: I Will Be Your Mother Figure | Encore
episodes.subtitle:
When people ask for advice, do they really want to hear what you have to say? Sometimes it's hardest to find a friend who can give just a simple, sympathetic ear.
Actor Laura Dern takes us deep into a friendship that experienced a unique evolution. This is an encore presentation.

episodes.title: The Shirt Stays On | With Finn Wittrock
episodes.subtitle: Getting undressed in front of your partner can be really hard. And for Jameson Rich, is was even more complicated. He writes about it in his piece, which is read by Finn Wittrock ("Write When You Get Work").

episodes.title: A Young Man's Game | With Stanley Tucci
episodes.subtitle: When Rand Richards Cooper was in his 40s, he was faced with a question: How late is too late to first become a dad? He writes about it in his essay, which is read by Stanley Tucci ("A Private War").

episodes.title: On A Serpentine Road | With Michelle Rodriguez
episodes.subtitle: How do we choose what to hold onto from loved ones after they've died? Doris Iarovici asks that question in her essay, which is read by Michelle Rodriguez ("Widows").

episodes.title: A Forgotten Prayer, Answered | With Mira Sorvino
episodes.subtitle: When Charlotte Bacon went to a temple in Bhutan, the place unlocked feelings in her that she hadn't truly realized were there. Her essay is read by Mira Sorvino ("StartUp").

episodes.title: Maddy Just Might Work | Encore
episodes.subtitle: Jennifer Finney Boylan -- an accomplished writer, academic and activist -- reads her own essay about coming out as transgender to her two young sons. This is an encore episode.

episodes.title: How To Break Up With A 2-Year-Old | With Busy Philipps
episodes.subtitle: We cross paths with so many people in our lives -- but only a few of them truly change the direction we thought we were headed in. Busy Philipps ("Busy Tonight") reads Laurie Sandell's piece, about the little girl who changed her path.

episodes.title: An Ancient Coda To My 21st-Century Divorce | With Amy Landecker
episodes.subtitle: After a divorce, it can feel like the last thing you want to do is revisit the past. But a ritual forced Cindy Chupack to do just that, in an essay read by actor Amy Landecker.

episodes.title: In The Waiting Room Of Estranged Spouses | Encore
episodes.subtitle: Lance Reddick, best known as Lt. Cedric Daniels on HBO's "The Wire," reads a story about infidelity and healing.

episodes.title: I Was Hardly a Perfect Fit | With John C. Reilly
episodes.subtitle: Tim Elhajj was a divorced dad who was desperate to connect with his son -- and went about it in an unconventional way. His essay is read by John C. Reilly (The Sisters Brothers).

episodes.title: The Plain, Unmarked Box Arrived | With Kristen Bell
episodes.subtitle: Would you buy a sex chair? Well, Lori Jakiela did -- and she writes about the chair, and the misadventures involved in trying to use it, in an essay that's read by Kristen Bell ("The Good Place.")

episodes.title: Escaping From A Dire Diagnosis On Match.com | With Rita Wilson
episodes.subtitle: Would you start online dating just to make your best friend feel better? Author Victoria Redel did that, and she writes about in her piece, which is read by actor and singer Rita Wilson ("Bigger Picture").

episodes.title: A Life Plan For Two | With Olivia Munn
episodes.subtitle: Some crushes are brief: the guy at the gym, the girl on Twitter, your barista. But others are epic -- and take on a life of their own. Olivia Munn ("The Predator") reads Marina Shifrin's essay.

episodes.title: Bonus: 81 Minutes
episodes.subtitle: We’re back in your feed to share a project we think you’ll love. It’s a new podcast called “Last Seen,” about the largest unsolved art heist in history -- the theft of thirteen irreplaceable pieces of art from Boston's Isabella Stewart Gardner museum.

episodes.title: Making A Judgment On Love | With Giancarlo Esposito
episodes.subtitle: On a normal day in 2004, Lloyd Zimmerman got the chance to fulfill a man's dying wish.  Giancarlo Esposito ("Better Call Saul") reads his piece, about the complications of a last request.

episodes.title: Learning Humanity From Dogs | With Ethan Hawke
episodes.subtitle: Ethan Hawke ("Blaze") reads an essay about how lonely it can be at rock bottom -- and how sometimes, taking care of someone else is the only way out.

episodes.title: Modern Love Playlist: In Sickness And In Health
episodes.subtitle: This playlist episode features stories about people whose relationships were challenged by illness -- and where the promise to stand by each other "in sickness and in health" was tested. It features stories read by Michael Shannon, Sarah Silverman, Chris Messina, Rebecca Hall, and Patina Miller.

episodes.title: Modern Love Playlist: Secrets
episodes.subtitle: It can feel easier to leave things unspoken than to find the right words to explain ourselves. But sooner or later, the things we keep from each other can come to define our relationships. This edition of Modern Love features a playlist of three of our favorite episodes about secrets, read by Danielle Brooks, Cynthia Nixon, and Uma Thurman.

episodes.title: The Secret To Marriage | With Sandra Oh
episodes.subtitle: Communication. Respect. Intimacy. Doing the dishes. Those are all things that have been called the secret to marriage. But Gabrielle Zevin has a different idea. Sandra Oh ("Killing Eve") reads her piece.

episodes.title: Bonus: Test of Time
episodes.subtitle: We know you appreciate a good love story ... so we're bringing you two stories of relationships that have stood the test of time, from another podcast from WBUR, called "Endless Thread." Hear the story of the couple featured in an iconic photo from Woodstock, and one about a relationship that started with a note sent in second grade.

episodes.title: Single Woman Seeking Manwich | With Awkwafina
episodes.subtitle: Let's face it. With the ghosting, inappropriate comments, and awkward small talk ... dating can be so bad it's hilarious. Awkwafina ("Crazy Rich Asians," "Oceans Eight") reads Sarah Moses's essay.

episodes.title: When Mothers Bully Back | With Ellie Kemper
episodes.subtitle: The emotions of parenting can feel completely out of control sometimes. Whether it's love, joy ... or, occasionally, rage. Susan Perabo writes about them in her essay, which is read by Ellie Kemper ("Unbreakable Kimmy Schmidt").

episodes.title: GPS For My Lost Identity | With Diane Guerrero
episodes.subtitle: Sometimes, our deepest loves aren't people at all -- they're the places that make us feel most like ourselves. Laura Dave tells a story about one of those places in her essay, which is read by Diane Guerrero ("Orange is the New Black").

episodes.title: Superheroes, Just for Each Other | With Mike Colter
episodes.subtitle: Peter Goodman thought that he could fix any problem by sweeping his wife off her feet. But when his daughter was born, that strategy failed him. His essay is read by Mike Colter ("Luke Cage.")

episodes.title: A Hiker’s Guide to Healing | With Cameron Esposito
episodes.subtitle: Aspen Matis decided to hike the Pacific Crest Trail because she was looking for solitude, safety, and escape. She writes about what she found there in her essay, read by actor and comic Cameron Esposito.

episodes.title: Catfishing Strangers To Find Myself | With Cory Michael Smith
episodes.subtitle: As a teenager in Finland, Kalle Oskari Mattila was trying to figure out who he was. For help, he turned to Pamela Anderson. Cory Michael Smith ("1985," "Gotham") performed his story live at the Provincetown Film Festival.

episodes.title: My Back-Seat View Of A Great Romance | With Chloë Grace Moretz
episodes.subtitle: "What did it mean that the most romantic thing I’d ever been a part of hadn’t even happened to me?" Chloë Grace Moretz ("The Miseducation of Cameron Post") reads Rachel Monroe's essay about watching a love story unfold from the sidelines.

episodes.title: Encore | Between The Bars
episodes.subtitle: Joshua Jackson ("The Affair") reads a story about life and love after 26 months in Iran's Evin Prison.  This is an encore presentation.

episodes.title: The Hunter-Gatherer, Parking Division | With Jason Alexander
episodes.subtitle: The challenge of finding the perfect partner is matched only by the challenge of finding the perfect parking space in New York City. Jason Alexander ("Seinfeld") reads Andy Raskin's essay, about the search for love and parking in Chinatown.

episodes.title: Finding My Own Rescuer | With Mandy Moore
episodes.subtitle: Mandy Moore ("This Is Us") reads Anna March's essay about disability, ability, and the misconceptions surrounding both.

episodes.title: A Fear Stripped Bare | With Sarah Shahi
episodes.subtitle: When she was growing up, Susan Sajadi thought that her mother was fearless.  It wasn't until years later that she realized the truth was much more complicated. Her piece is read by Sarah Shahi, who stars in NBC's "Reverie."

episodes.title: Love Stories In 13 Words | Modern Love Bonus Episode

episodes.title: Modern Love Encore | Marry A Man Who Loves His Mother
episodes.subtitle: Constance Wu of the ABC comedy "Fresh Off The Boat" reads a story about a wife, a mother-in-law and the unlikely story that brought them together.

episodes.title: The Language Of Love | With Saoirse Ronan
episodes.subtitle: Saoirse Ronan ("On Chesil Beach") reads an essay about how a language barrier impacts the relationship between a young woman and an Iraqi doctor.

episodes.title: A Measure of Desire | With Kim Dickens
episodes.subtitle: Sometimes it's the things that go unspoken in a relationship that are the most important. Andrea Jarrell found that out not long after moving to Maine with her husband -- and she writes about it in her piece, read by Kim Dickens ("Fear the Walking Dead").

episodes.title: When Eve And Eve Bit The Apple | With Rachel Weisz
episodes.subtitle: Kristen Scharold was an evangelical Christian who was starting to look for a husband. Then, a new relationship caused a crisis of faith. Rachel Weisz ("Disobedience") reads Kristen's essay.

episodes.title: Signs, Wonders, and Fates Fulfilled | With Linda Cardellini
episodes.subtitle: After Stephanie Saldaña moved to an ancient monastery in Syria, she thought she'd found her calling. But when she met a novice monk there, she had to rethink everything. Linda Cardellini ("Bloodline") reads Stephanie's essay.

episodes.title: Boy, What A Fabulous Baker | With Abbi Jacobson
episodes.subtitle: Abbi Jacobson ("6 Balloons," "Broad City") reads an essay about a carboholic who falls for a baker -- and his bread.

episodes.title: A Cup From The Fountain Of Youth | With Mel Rodriguez
episodes.subtitle: When you're at a bar and someone starts paying more attention to you than you expect -- how do you react? Mel Rodriguez ("Overboard," "The Last Man on Earth") reads Andy Christie's essay, about trying to navigate an unexpected flirtation.

episodes.title: A Brother As Significant As Any Other | With Jeffrey Bowyer-Chapman

episodes.title: R We D8ting? | With Krysten Ritter

episodes.title: Learning To Embrace Sexuality's Gray Areas | With Nico Tortorella

episodes.subtitle: Betty Gilpin of Netflix's "G.L.O.W." reads a story about life after abortion.

episodes.title: Just Friends? | With Tony Hale
episodes.subtitle: Emmy Award-winning actor Tony Hale of HBO's "Veep" reads an essay about breaking up, moving on (or not), and reading between the lines.

episodes.title: Live Without Me | With Catherine Keener
episodes.subtitle: Two-time Oscar nominee Catherine Keener reads Katherine Friedman Holland's essay about a near-death experience on an airplane.

episodes.title: One Last Swirl | With Jason Alexander
episodes.subtitle: Jason Alexander -- best known as George Costanza from the iconic 90's sit-com "Seinfeld" -- reads a story that explores mortality with the help of a resilient pet fish.

episodes.title: Estranged Spouses | With Lance Reddick
episodes.subtitle: Lance Reddick, best known as Lt. Cedric Daniels on HBO's "The Wire," reads a story about infidelity and healing.

episodes.title: Live From New York | With Michaela Watkins, Amirah Vann and Lauren Molina
episodes.subtitle: Michaela Watkins, Amirah Vann and Lauren Molina read Modern Love essays live in front of a studio audience.

episodes.title: Fighting Words | With Alysia Reiner
episodes.subtitle: Alysia Reiner of Orange is the New Black delivers a story about what happens when a stable relationship suddenly takes a hard left turn.

episodes.title: The Doorman | With Cecily Strong
episodes.subtitle: Saturday Night Live's Cecily Strong reads a story about a woman's friendship with her doorman.

episodes.title: The Wait | Modern Love Bonus Episode
episodes.subtitle: We asked you to tell us about a time when you "waited for love," and you answered from all over the world. This bonus episode of Modern Love features some of those stories.

episodes.title: Coming Out As A Modern Family | With Maria Bello
episodes.subtitle: Actress Maria Bello reads her own essay about opening up to her son and the public about her love life.

episodes.title: How I Got To Here | With Katie Couric
episodes.subtitle: Katie Couric reads Leslie Lehr's Modern Love essay about learning the true depth of her relationship with her husband.

episodes.title: Friends Without Benefits | With Taissa Farmiga
episodes.subtitle: Taissa Farmiga reads a story about "friends without benefits" who spend years circling each other without defining their drawn-out, nebulous relationship.

episodes.title: A Heart Outrun | With Colin Farrell
episodes.subtitle: Colin Farrell reads the story of man who had given up on love -- until it showed up at his door.

episodes.title: A Second Embrace | With Cheryl Strayed
episodes.subtitle: Cheryl Strayed -- co-host of WBUR's "Dear Sugar" podcast and author of the best-selling memoir "Wild" -- reads a story about taking a second chance on love.

episodes.title: I See My Superhero | With Sarah Silverman
episodes.subtitle: Sarah Silverman brings us a story of unconditional love ... with a few conditions.

episodes.title: Between The Bars | With Joshua Jackson
episodes.subtitle: Joshua Jackson reads a story about life and love after 26 months in Iran's Evin Prison.

episodes.title: My First Lesson In Motherhood | With Connie Britton
episodes.subtitle: Connie Britton narrates a story about a new mom and a tiny infant whose young life is checkered with mysteries both big and small.

episodes.title: Maddy Just Might Work | With Jennifer Finney Boylan
episodes.subtitle: Jennifer Finney Boylan -- an accomplished writer, academic and activist -- reads her own essay about coming out as transgender to her two young sons.

episodes.title: Broken, Not Bound | With America Ferrera
episodes.subtitle: America Ferrera reads the story of an African aid worker, and an event that drastically shifted her perspective.

episodes.title: Mom/Not Mom/Aunt | With Jesse Tyler Ferguson
episodes.subtitle: Jesse Tyler Ferguson reads a story about a brother's unique need and sister's selfless gift.

episodes.title: Where It All Started | Modern Love Bonus Episode
episodes.subtitle: Modern Love listeners share true stories of meeting their significant other.

episodes.title: A Millennial's Guide To Kissing | With Emmy Rossum
episodes.subtitle: Emmy Rossum reads a story about a 12-hour relationship. On an airplane.

episodes.title: Seesawing Libidos | With Stephen Bogardus
episodes.subtitle: Tony-nominated actor Stephen Bogardus brings us a tale of two sex drives.

episodes.title: Leaps of Faith | Modern Love Bonus Episode
episodes.subtitle: We love hearing your stories of love, loss and redemption. This bonus episode features listener-submitted stories involving "leaps of faith."

episodes.title: A Faithful Leap | With Amber Tamblyn
episodes.subtitle: Amber Tamblyn brings us the story of a leap of faith so dramatic, it's straight out of a movie.

episodes.title: In Darkness And In Light | With Patina Miller
episodes.subtitle: Patina Miller narrates a story about one woman who has a seemingly average life and marriage -- except for the fact that she's slowly going blind.

episodes.title: Magically Interrupted | With Michael Shannon
episodes.subtitle: Michael Shannon reads an essay that explores how Alzheimer's put one family back together.

episodes.title: A 'Modern Love' Audio Valentine
episodes.subtitle: An audio valentine from Modern Love listeners -- for Modern Love listeners.

episodes.title: 'The Plunge' | With Dakota Fanning
episodes.subtitle: Dakota Fanning narrates an essay about a falling in love and falling off a cliff -- literally.

episodes.title: 'An Interlude Of Clarity' | With Judd Apatow
episodes.subtitle: Judd Apatow reads a story about a man whose perfect date ends up in the emergency room.

episodes.title: Not So Simple Math | With Sarah Paulson
episodes.subtitle: Sarah Paulson narrates this week's episode -- a story about a woman's decision to put up her child for an open adoption.

episodes.title: One Last Swirl | With Jason Alexander
episodes.subtitle: Jason Alexander narrates this story about a man projecting his deepest thoughts of mortality onto his pet fish.

episodes.title: Missed Connection | With Lauren Molina
episodes.subtitle: Welcome to our first episode. Lauren Molina narrates a story about a romance that begins on an unlikely website -- Craigslist.

episodes.title: Introducing 'Modern Love: The Podcast'
episodes.subtitle: Explore the trials and tribulations of love in these deeply personal essays. A collaboration of The New York Times and WBUR in Boston, Modern Love: The Podcast features the popular New York Times column, with readings by notable personalities and updates from the essayists themselves. Join host Meghna Chakrabarti (WBUR) and Modern Love editor Daniel Jones (NYT) -- and fall in love at first listen.
